people.quickstart: Colored squares represent companies (see Options tab above). The white numbers indicate the total board membership of each company in the current year. The size of the squares is proportional to total board membership. Names represent presidents, vice presidents, or individuals who were on the board of at least two companies from 1872 to 1894, and have board membership in the current view (currently displayed year) or previous view (previously displayed year). Names shown in standard type have board membership in the current view and also had board membership in the previous view. Italic names are new in the current view. Floating names had board membership in the previous view but have no board membership in the current view. Floating companies had board members in the previous view but have no board members in the current view. Gray lines represent board memberships in the current view that also existed in the previous view. Green lines represent board memberships that are new in the current view. Click on and drag a node to move it and lock it to its new position. Double click to unlock.
people.help:
This visualization represents the board membership of 11 major U.S. railroad companies during the 22 year period from 1872 to 1894 as a set of dynamic graphs which trace through time and space the movements of the men who shaped The West.

Advanced

Click on and drag a node to move it and lock it to its new position. Double click to unlock.

Network Zoom is a global multiplier that modulates the strength of all connections in the visualization equally. It does not reflect any properties of the data itself and is meant only as a tool that can be used to adjust the size of the graphs if they are too big for the screen.
